                "ExtraWhitespace", {
                 Cell[
                 "Simulations are stateful: CreatePhysicsModel allocates a \
persistent physics world in memory, and DestroyPhysicsModel frees it. Each \
world is identified by an integer handle.\nBodies are classified as either \
DynamicBody (affected by gravity and collisions) or FixedBody (immovable \
obstacles/floors).\nEach body has physical material properties that can be \
set via options: \"Density\" (default 1.0), \"Restitution\" (bounciness, \
default 0.5), and \"Friction\" (default 0.5).\nInitial velocities can be \
assigned to dynamic bodies using the \"Velocity\" option.\nBody orientations \
are tracked internally as quaternions and converted to/from 3\[Times]3 \
rotation matrices for compatibility with GeometricTransformation.\nTime \
evolution is performed with PhysicsModelIterate, which steps the simulation \
by a given number of substeps at a fixed time increment dt. Smaller dt values \
yield more accurate results.\nPhysicsModelEvolve is a convenience function \
that collects a sequence of PhysicsModelObject frames for animation.\n\
PhysicsModelPlot renders the current state as a Graphics3D scene, \
automatically applying positions and rotations returned by the engine.\n\
PhysicsBoundaryBox generates six invisible FixedBody walls to confine objects \
within a bounding region.\nPhysicsModelVideo produces an AnimationVideo from \
a list of simulation frames.\nThe Rapier library is compiled as a \
platform-specific shared library (.dylib on macOS, .so on Linux, .dll on \
Windows) and loaded from the paclet's LibraryResources/$SystemID/ directory \
at package initialization.", "Notes", TaggingRules -> {}, 
                  CellChangeTimes -> {{3.985007074001012*^9, 
                   3.985007109509831*^9}}, CellTags -> "DefaultContent", 
                  CellID -> 1253032187]}]; 
